<h1>{{ title }}</h1>

<div class="demo-section">
  <h2>1. Using the Paired Shortcode</h2>
  <p>You can wrap any HTML content with Enhance custom elements:</p>
  
  {% enhance %}
    <my-header></my-header>
  {% endenhance %}
</div>

<div class="demo-section">
  <h2>2. Multiple Elements Together</h2>
  <p>You can use multiple custom elements in a single shortcode:</p>
  
  {% enhance %}
    <my-header></my-header>
    <div>
      <p>Regular HTML content works fine alongside custom elements.</p>
    </div>
    <my-footer></my-footer>
  {% endenhance %}
</div>

<div class="demo-section">
  <h2>3. Single Element Shortcode</h2>
  <p>Render a single element directly:</p>
  
  {% enhanceElement "my-header" %}
</div>

<div class="demo-section">
  <h2>4. Nested in Markdown</h2>
  <p>Since this works in any template, you can even use it in Markdown content!</p>
</div>

<div class="demo-section">
  <h2>5. State Passing</h2>
  <p>The <code>initialState</code> from the front matter is available to all elements:</p>
  
  {% enhance %}
    <my-footer></my-footer>
  {% endenhance %}
  
  <p>Check the footer above - it should show the state from the front matter.</p>
</div>

<div class="demo-section">
  <h2>6. Interactive Element (SSR + Client-Side)</h2>
  <p>This counter is server-side rendered, then enhanced with client-side interactivity:</p>
  
  {% enhance %}
    <example-counter></example-counter>
  {% endenhance %}
  
  <p>The counter is fully rendered by the server (great for SEO), then JavaScript adds interactivity!</p>
</div>

<div class="demo-section">
  <h2>How This Works</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>✅ Custom elements are defined in <code>elements/*.mjs</code></li>
    <li>✅ Elements are server-side rendered with <code>@enhance/ssr</code></li>
    <li>✅ Works in Nunjucks, Liquid, Markdown, HTML, and .11ty.js files</li>
    <li>✅ State can be passed via front matter, data files, or global data</li>
    <li>✅ Client-side JavaScript can enhance elements after SSR</li>
  </ul>
</div>

